</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC66FFE2F54936C2FCB2F95D" blockId="11.[347,1255,1707,1758]" pageId="11" pageNumber="788">
: elytra unmodified; posterior margin of sternite VIII broadly convex, in the middle truncate (
<figureCitation id="133623E5DC66FFE2F58236A6FD96F95D" box="[443,518,1736,1758]" captionStart="Figs 36-42" captionStartId="11.[347,387,1604,1624]" captionTargetBox="[347,1247,771,1587]" captionTargetId="figure-141@11.[347,1260,1116,1593]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36-42: Geostiba spinosula nov.sp.: (36) male pronotum, elytra, and abdominal segment III (holotype); (37) head in lateral view; (38-39) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (40) apical lobe of paramere; (41) female sternite VIII; (42) spermatheca. Scale bars: 36: 0.5 mm; 37: 0.2 mm; 38-42: 0.1 mm." pageId="11" pageNumber="788">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
); spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation id="133623E5DC66FFE2F6EA36A6FCB2F95D" box="[723,802,1736,1758]" captionStart="Figs 36-42" captionStartId="11.[347,387,1604,1624]" captionTargetBox="[347,1247,771,1587]" captionTargetId="figure-141@11.[347,1260,1116,1593]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36-42: Geostiba spinosula nov.sp.: (36) male pronotum, elytra, and abdominal segment III (holotype); (37) head in lateral view; (38-39) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (40) apical lobe of paramere; (41) female sternite VIII; (42) spermatheca. Scale bars: 36: 0.5 mm; 37: 0.2 mm; 38-42: 0.1 mm." pageId="11" pageNumber="788">Fig. 42.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC66FFE2F5623680FB77F880" blockId="11.[347,1255,1773,1795]" box="[347,1255,1773,1795]" pageId="11" pageNumber="788">E t y m o l o g y: The name, diminutive of spinose (Lat., adj.: thorny), refers to the</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC61FFE5F736310BFCA3FEF9" blockId="12.[783,819,357,378]" box="[783,819,357,378]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">789</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC61FFE5F56231DEFE5DFE60" blockId="12.[347,1254,432,483]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">minute body size and the presence of a small spine-like process at the posterior margin of tergite VII.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC61FFE5F562319DFD01FC5E" blockId="12.[347,1255,499,989]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: Based on external (pale coloration, strongly reduced eyes), as well as on various derived male primary and secondary sexual characters (elytra with sharply edged lateral margins, presence of a tubercle on tergite III, presence of a spine-like process at the posterior margin of tergite VII, morphology of the median lobe of the aedeagus, shape and chaetotaxy of the apical lobe of the paramere), 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F05C3206FB77FDFD" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2007" box="[1125,1255,616,638]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosula">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F05C3206FB77FDFD" box="[1125,1255,616,638]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. spinosula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F5C032E8FDFAFD18" box="[505,618,645,667]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F5C032E8FDFAFD18" box="[505,618,645,667]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C4291DC61FFE5F6D332EBFC12FD18" author="ASSING V" box="[746,898,645,667]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" pagination="1047 - 1070" refId="ref6682" refString="ASSING V. (2005 b): New species and new records of Eastern Mediterranean Geostiba THOMSON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 37 (2): 1047 - 1070." type="journal article" year="2005">ASSING 2005b</bibRefCitation>
), which previously included three species from central southern 
<collectingCountry id="F31A7FF0DC61FFE5F6B532CCFD77FD3B" box="[652,743,674,696]" name="Turkey" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F6C832CDFC23FD3B" authority="ASSING" authorityName="ASSING" box="[753,947,674,696]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F6C832CDFCF0FD3B" box="[753,864,674,696]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. confusa</emphasis>
ASSING
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F7F932CDFB05FD3B" authority="ASSING" authorityName="ASSING" box="[960,1173,674,696]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bigibbera">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F7F932CDFBD1FD3B" box="[960,1089,674,696]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. bigibbera</emphasis>
ASSING
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F0F732CDFDCCFD56" authority="ASSING. Among" authorityName="ASSING. Among" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbera">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F0F732CDFE3AFD56" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. gibbera</emphasis>
ASSING. Among
</taxonomicName>
these species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F6C532AEFCEFFD56" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2007" box="[764,895,703,725]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosula">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F6C532AEFCEFFD56" box="[764,895,703,725]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. spinosula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar and related to the geographically close 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F60E32B3FD37FD70" authorityName="ASSING. Among" authorityYear="2005" box="[567,679,733,755]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbera">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F60E32B3FD37FD70" box="[567,679,733,755]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. gibbera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is known only from one locality approximately 
<quantity id="4CF59285DC61FFE5F5623294FE0EFC93" box="[347,414,762,784]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" unit="km" value="30.0">30 km</quantity>
SSW of Kahramanmaraú. It is distinguished from this species by smaller body size, distinctly paler coloration (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F6C93376FCF8FCAE" authorityName="ASSING. Among" authorityYear="2005" box="[752,872,791,813]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbera">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F6C93376FCF8FCAE" box="[752,872,791,813]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. gibbera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reddish yellow), less pronounced microsculpture especially of the pronotum, shorter antennae, a more pronounced tubercle on the male tergite III, a differently shaped process of the male tergite VII, the different morphology of the aedeagus (ventral process shorter, not bent in lateral view, and apically less acute in ventral view), and a spermatheca with a more slender capsule and a shorter duct. For illustrations of the habitus and the sexual characters of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D44E3DC61FFE5F07733C4FB2EFC43" authorityName="ASSING. Among" authorityYear="2005" box="[1102,1214,938,960]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbera">
<emphasis id="B979E372DC61FFE5F07733C4FB2EFC43" box="[1102,1214,938,960]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">G. gibbera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see the figures in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C4291DC61FFE5F5DE33A9FD1DFC5E" author="ASSING V" box="[487,653,967,989]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" pagination="1047 - 1070" refId="ref6682" refString="ASSING V. (2005 b): New species and new records of Eastern Mediterranean Geostiba THOMSON (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 37 (2): 1047 - 1070." type="journal article" year="2005">ASSING (2005b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB23F60DC61FFE5F5623383FE20FBD9" blockId="12.[347,1255,1004,1114]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d b i o n o m i c s: The 
<typeStatus id="54B681C2DC61FFE5F7B33383FC3EFB81" box="[906,942,1005,1026]" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated some 45 southwest of Kahramanmaraú, central southern 
<collectingCountry id="F31A7FF0DC61FFE5F7753464FC33FBA3" box="[844,931,1034,1056]" name="Turkey" pageId="12" pageNumber="789">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="133623E5DC61FFE5F78A3464FC69FBA3" box="[947,1017,1034,1056]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="5.[347,392,897,917]" captionTargetBox="[347,1254,432,897]" captionTargetId="figure-7@5.[347,1253,433,889]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Map 1: Distributions of Geostiba janbellini nov.sp. (filled circle), G. atrioculata nov.sp. (open circle), and G. spinosula nov.sp. (square) in southern Anatolia." pageId="12" pageNumber="789">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The specimens were collected under stones on a grassy slope at an altitude of 
<quantity id="4CF59285DC61FFE5F7E63449FBA1FBBE" box="[991,1073,1063,1085]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="12" pageNumber="789" unit="m" value="1200.0">1200 m</quantity>
(BRACHAT pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
